dismissalComment.html: lovely catch by Sibanda to give Ncube a maiden ODI wicket. Not that this is what you can call a fielder's wicket alone. Ncube stays short of a length even as Nicol charges at him, the bounce and the line cramp him up, and he ends up slicing it square on the off side. Sibanda runs back from point - turns around and runs - and takes it over his shoulder

Oh what have you done Elton? Length ball all right, but he swipes across it, the head falls away, the bat swings down the wrong line, and the middle stump is uprooted. The usually soft-spoken Oram has a lot to say now. Not sure if it is directed at Chigumbura

dismissalComment.html: this is catching practice really. There is a short midwicket in place, the ball is flighted on middle and off, it is turning, and with the turn he offers a simple catch to B McCullum to make it an all McCullum dismissal. Unlike Watling, though, Sibanda gets a regulation, non-exotic duck

dismissalComment.html: These McCullum brothers have magnets or what? Poor analogy because the ball is not metal. Anyway, another catch for the McCullums, and what a big wicket. Taibu looks for the inside-out drive, hits it uppishly, and B McCullum dives to his left to take this. That's four catches between the brothers out of the five wickets to fall

commentPreTextItems.html: Ncube walks out, gets a knock on the glove from Price. All he has to do is run like hell when Waller calls him, Anybody thinking of Lance Klusener? This is not Australia and South Africa, but their neighbours

commentTextItems.html: Waller does it as coolly as he has done in the rest of his innings. Short of a length, outside off, pushes it with an open face, past short cover, between point and cover-point, and yes they run like hell. I wonder if he thought of hitting a boundary to get the hundred? Who cares? Zimbabwe have won. Their biggest chase ever

commentPostTextItems.html: New Zealand get a shield for winning the series. They don't look really kicked. The loss must be gutting for them. Jesse Ryder of all people gets to uncork the champagne. Those are the scenes we leave you with. Lovely day of cricket. Cheers for tuning in

Time to listen to the Taylors and the Man of the Match. Brendan Taylor is the Man of the Series. He says, "Awesome feeling. Nice to end the way we did. Nice to salvage a bit of pride. All credit to New Zealand. We will take a lot out of this. We have a little bit of momentum now. From start to finish the guys were positive in their approach. No nails left. The crowd always turns up, this one is for them, and everyone who has shown up in the past."

Malcolm Waller is the Man of the Match. "Feeling really good," says he. "Good to come out winning this game. Great. To take it right through the end was very good. Having Elto striking it s well was great. I was a bit nervous at times, but Elton took the pressure off with the big hits, and Razor in the end was great."

"I thought 320 was a par score. It was a pretty good wicket. The way Kane batted was fantastic, but Zimbabwe batted superbly," says Ross. "The story of this series has been, if you drop catches, you lose matches. I was a bit rusty and enjoyed some luck with the bat. Kane was outstanding. We could have bowled a bit straighter, but I am going to put my hand up. I dropped two easy catches, and if you do that you are going to lose matches."

Stumps are taken out, hands are shaken, hugs exchanged. This is a huge day for Zimbabwe cricket. Elton Chigumbura says before the ball he thought he would punch it down the ground, but the impulse took over. Just an example of how easy the game looks when played with fingers and a keyboard. "Sid, printed in triplet and the carbon paper joins the meal...Enjoy!!! this is a good day to die! :)" Although I don't like the first half of Luke's email, the latter half sums up just how much this means to Zimbabwe fans. Liam Brickhill must be dancing somewhere too. "Three consecutive Taylor centuries on the losing team? Maybe they should both score a ton next time." Brendan, that's what kept this from being a tie. Had Brendan reached his hundred I am sure we would have had a tie. Ironic that Ross Taylor himself dropped two-and-a-half catches in the end

dismissalText.commentary: Ray Price c BB McCullum b Oram 2 (7b 0x4 0x6 15m) SR: 28.57

commentTextItems.html: the game stays alive, but Price might have done just enough. Short of a length, Price tries to clear the leg-side field. The top edge goes nowhere, but Waller makes sure he moves to the striking end by the time the catch is taken
yorker, hit to short midwicket, sent back
Taylor has choked. He has dropped Waller thrice. This is a dolly. Taylor had just moved to short midwicket, and Waller hit straight at him. Out through the hands

commentPreTextItems.html: Big Jake Jacob Oram to bowl the last over. Can he pull a rabbit out here? New Zealand's best bet would be to give him the single here, and then tie Pierce to this end

commentTextItems.html: Taylor has put down a half chance and is down on his haunches. Slower short ball, mis-hit towards midwicket, high to Taylor's right, who leaps, outstretches his right hand, touches the ball, but can't hold onto it. What's more? He has parried it wide of long-on to allow the second

commentPreTextItems.html: If he gets a single here, this is Zimbabwe's game. Or will he go for the hit to end it now?

commentTextItems.html: no, he has worked too hard to risk it in one low-percentage shot now. He pushes this to long-off for one, and keeps strike

image.caption: Ray Price
image.longCaption: Ray Price portrait, World Cup 2011, February 11, 2011

commentTextItems.html: into the pads again, helped away to the left of short fine and to the right of deep square. Easy two. This is sensible stuff
swept away crisply, takes a single amid huge cheers from the crowd

commentPreTextItems.html: Interesting now. Men come up for Price

commentTextItems.html: full and straight, hits him on the pad, Ryder is really close at short fine
short of a length, punched away square for one
full on the pads, hit to Taylor at midwicket, Price is sent back, Taylor fires in a throw and misses. N McCullum runs from mid-off to back up and save one

commentPreTextItems.html: "This is awesome I am ashamed by the fact that I am loving Woodcock's performance... Just for what it might imply." Ken is a confused Kiwi right now. Woodcock continues, though. Two hits away are Zimbabwe

commentTextItems.html: fired down the leg side, Watling does well to collect this. Target down in singe figures
Price is a champ. Digs out a yorker, and belts out a NO. Clear thinking

image.caption: Ray Price
image.longCaption: Ray Price portrait, World Cup 2011, February 11, 2011

commentTextItems.html: full and straight now, hit to long-on, gives Price just the one ball to survive

Waller moves into the 90s, the crowd find back their voice and their moves. This is turning out to be a poor over. Length ball on the pads with short fine leg up. Waller says thank you very much and flicks him over that man
Waller keeps the game alive. Short and wide, he goes for the upper-cut, deliberately to miss point. Is he the iron man?

commentPreTextItems.html: The field comes up now. No easy singles

commentTextItems.html: short of a length, into the pads, helped away with the angle for a single to fine leg

commentPreTextItems.html: "I think its really irresponsible for Cricinfo not to have a hotline that Zimbabwe supporters can phone into, and talk them off the edge..." Dylan, next you will ask for shrinks and couches. And just imagine what all we will need for Pakistan fans. Aldridge comes back. He will bowl Nos 48 and 50

commentTextItems.html: short of a length, cut away to sweeper-cover, New Zealand won't mind the single

commentPreTextItems.html: Waller has to take more control now. He has to be in his partners' ears and make sure they don't play stupid shots like the two previous batsmen have. All I know is bad shots with Ray Price will come over his dead body

commentTextItems.html: full, on the pads, defends, over to Waller for the next over

dismissalText.commentary: Hamilton Masakadza b Oram 36 (56b 3x4 0x6 102m) SR: 64.28

dismissalComment.html: Silence. You can hear a chair creek at Queen's. Masakadza slogs across one, Oram stays straight. On a length it pitches, beats the swinging bat, and hits top of middle

headshotImage.longCaption: Andy McKay player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Brendan Taylor c NL McCullum b McKay 75 (65b 7x4 2x6 68m) SR: 115.38

dismissalComment.html: What a catch. These McCullums have wings, man. Taylor tries to clear mid-off, and seems like he will do it. Nathan McCullum, though, waits for a second, and then times his jump go perfection to make this catch look easy

headshotImage.longCaption: Andy McKay player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Tatenda Taibu c BB McCullum b McKay 53 (39b 4x4 2x6 53m) SR: 135.89

dismissalComment.html: These McCullum brothers have magnets or what? Poor analogy because the ball is not metal. Anyway, another catch for the McCullums, and what a big wicket. Taibu looks for the inside-out drive, hits it uppishly, and B McCullum dives to his left to take this. That's four catches between the brothers out of the five wickets to fall

dismissalText.commentary: Forster Mutizwa c NL McCullum b Nicol 0 (2b 0x4 0x6 5m) SR: 0

dismissalComment.html: Boy these McCullums are flying everywhere. This is short, turns a touch extra, hurries him into the an uppish flick, and N McCullum goes parallel to his left to make this catch happen. He even manages to make it look easy

dismissalText.commentary: Malcolm Waller not out 99 (74b 10x4 1x6 108m) SR: 133.78

headshotImage.caption: Jacob Oram player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Jacob Oram player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Elton Chigumbura b Oram 47 (43b 3x4 3x6 64m) SR: 109.3

dismissalComment.html: Oh what have you done Elton? Length ball all right, but he swipes across it, the head falls away, the bat swings down the wrong line, and the middle stump is uprooted. The usually soft-spoken Oram has a lot to say now. Not sure if it is directed at Chigumbura

dismissalText.commentary: Keegan Meth b Woodcock 0 (2b 0x4 0x6 3m) SR: 0

dismissalComment.html: poor poor cricket from Meth. Charges at him without any purpose. Woodcock bowls a straight length ball, he wafts down the wrong line, and is bowled. Mindless really

dismissalText.commentary: Natsai M'shangwe b Woodcock 7 (10b 0x4 1x6 9m) SR: 70

dismissalComment.html: Stunned silence again. Natsai jumps out of the crease and swings blindly again. Middle stump knocked over. Woodcock is elated, Waller looks on

dismissalText.commentary: Ray Price c BB McCullum b Oram 2 (7b 0x4 0x6 15m) SR: 28.57

dismissalText.commentary: Njabulo Ncube not out 0 (0b 0x4 0x6 1m) SR: 0

dismissalComment.html: this is catching practice really. Unlike Watling, though, Sibanda gets a regulation, non-exotic duck
